---
import SiteLayout from '../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": "The Complete Guide to Smoking Meat",
      "description": "Master the art of smoking meat: wood selection, temperature control, brisket, ribs, pulled pork, and equipment recommendations.",
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "28grams"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What temperature to smoke brisket?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The ideal temperature for smoking a brisket is typically between 225°F and 250°F. Your target internal temperature should be around 200°F to 205°F for optimal tenderness."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the best wood for smoking?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The best wood depends on the meat. Hickory and oak are great for beef and pork, while milder woods like apple and cherry are perfect for poultry and fish."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How long to smoke ribs?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Pork spare ribs generally take 5 to 6 hours using the popular 3-2-1 method (3 hours unwrapped, 2 hours wrapped in foil, 1 hour unwrapped to set the sauce) at 225°F."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the stall when smoking meat?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The stall occurs when the internal temperature of large cuts of meat, like brisket or pork shoulder, stops rising (usually around 160°F) due to evaporative cooling. Wrapping the meat can help push through the stall."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Should I soak my wood chips before smoking?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Generally, it is not recommended to soak wood chips. Soaking creates steam rather than clean smoke, which can lower your smoker's temperature and produce a bitter flavor."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
};

export const meta = {
  title: "The Complete Guide to Smoking Meat",
  description: "Master the art of smoking meat: wood selection, temperature control, brisket, ribs, pulled pork, and equipment recommendations.",
  category: "guide",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="28grams"
  title="The Complete Guide to Smoking Meat"
  description="Master the art of smoking meat: wood selection, temperature control, brisket, ribs, pulled pork, and equipment recommendations."
  canonical="https://28grams.vip/guide-smoking-complete"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-5 py-12">
    <header class="text-center mb-12">
      <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-4">The Complete Guide to Smoking Meat</h1>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Master the art of smoking meat: wood selection, temperature control, classic cuts, and equipment recommendations.</p>
    </header>

    <!-- Section 1: Smoking Basics -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">1. Smoking Basics</h2>
      <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 shadow-sm">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-3">Low and Slow</h3>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">Smoking meat is the ultimate exercise in patience. By cooking tough cuts of meat at a low temperature (typically 225&deg;F - 275&deg;F) over a long period, the tough connective tissues (collagen) break down into tender, juicy gelatin.</p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-3">Smoke Ring Science</h3>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">The coveted "smoke ring" is a pink discoloration just beneath the surface of the meat. It's not actually a sign of smoke penetration, but a chemical reaction between the myoglobin in the meat and the nitric oxide (NO) and carbon monoxide (CO) produced by burning wood.</p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-3">Bark Formation</h3>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">"Bark" is the delicious, dark, crusty exterior of smoked meat. It forms through the Maillard reaction and the polymerization of fats and spices. A good bark requires a balance of rub (like salt and pepper), proper smoke, and time unwrapped in the heat.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 2: Wood Selection Guide -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">2. Wood Selection Guide</h2>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-6">Choosing the right wood is crucial as it acts as a seasoning for your meat. Here is a quick reference guide to popular smoking woods.</p>

      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm hover:border-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">Hickory</h4>
          <span class="inline-block px-2 py-1 text-xs font-bold rounded bg-red-900/30 text-red-400 mb-2">Strong</span>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)]">The quintessential BBQ wood. Sweet, hearty, and bacon-like. Great for pork and beef, but can be overpowering in large amounts.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm hover:border-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">Oak</h4>
          <span class="inline-block px-2 py-1 text-xs font-bold rounded bg-yellow-900/30 text-yellow-400 mb-2">Medium</span>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)]">The king of Texas BBQ. Provides a clean, steady smoke with a robust flavor that perfectly complements brisket without overpowering it.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm hover:border-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">Cherry</h4>
          <span class="inline-block px-2 py-1 text-xs font-bold rounded bg-green-900/30 text-green-400 mb-2">Mild</span>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Sweet and fruity. Cherry is prized for imparting a beautiful dark mahogany red color to the meat's bark. Excellent with pork and chicken.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm hover:border-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">Mesquite</h4>
          <span class="inline-block px-2 py-1 text-xs font-bold rounded bg-red-900/30 text-red-400 mb-2">Very Strong</span>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Intense and earthy. Mesquite burns hot and fast, making it better for grilling or brief smoking sessions. Best used sparingly on dark meats.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 3: Temperature & Time -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">3. Temperature & Time</h2>
      <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 shadow-sm">
        <div class="mb-6">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-2">The Stall</h3>
          <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">When smoking large cuts like brisket or pork shoulder, the internal temperature often plateaus around 160&deg;F. This "stall" is caused by evaporative cooling as the meat sweats. To overcome it, you can either patiently wait it out or wrap the meat (the "Texas Crutch").</p>
        </div>

        <div class="mb-6">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-2">Wrapping (Foil vs. Butcher Paper)</h3>
          <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Wrapping accelerates the cooking process and retains moisture. Aluminum foil creates a tight seal (braising the meat), which softens the bark. Pink peach butcher paper allows steam to escape, preserving your carefully cultivated bark while still pushing through the stall.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Target Temperatures Cheat Sheet</h3>
          <div class="overflow-x-auto">
            <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse">
              <thead>
                <tr class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] border-b border-[var(--border-color)]">
                  <th class="p-3 text-[var(--text-secondary)] font-semibold text-sm">Cut</th>
                  <th class="p-3 text-[var(--text-secondary)] font-semibold text-sm">Smoker Temp</th>
                  <th class="p-3 text-[var(--text-secondary)] font-semibold text-sm">Target Internal</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr class="border-b border-[var(--border-color)] hover:bg-[var(--bg-color)]/50 transition-colors">
                  <td class="p-3 font-medium text-white">Brisket</td>
                  <td class="p-3 text-[var(--text-secondary)] font-mono text-sm">225&deg;F - 250&deg;F</td>
                  <td class="p-3 text-[var(--accent-color)] font-mono text-sm">200&deg;F - 205&deg;F</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-[var(--border-color)] hover:bg-[var(--bg-color)]/50 transition-colors">
                  <td class="p-3 font-medium text-white">Pork Shoulder</td>
                  <td class="p-3 text-[var(--text-secondary)] font-mono text-sm">225&deg;F - 250&deg;F</td>
                  <td class="p-3 text-[var(--accent-color)] font-mono text-sm">200&deg;F - 205&deg;F</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-[var(--border-color)] hover:bg-[var(--bg-color)]/50 transition-colors">
                  <td class="p-3 font-medium text-white">Pork Ribs</td>
                  <td class="p-3 text-[var(--text-secondary)] font-mono text-sm">225&deg;F - 250&deg;F</td>
                  <td class="p-3 text-[var(--accent-color)] font-mono text-sm">195&deg;F - 205&deg;F</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="hover:bg-[var(--bg-color)]/50 transition-colors">
                  <td class="p-3 font-medium text-white">Whole Chicken</td>
                  <td class="p-3 text-[var(--text-secondary)] font-mono text-sm">275&deg;F - 325&deg;F</td>
                  <td class="p-3 text-[var(--accent-color)] font-mono text-sm">165&deg;F (Breast)</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] italic">Need precise planning? Check out our <a href="/smoking-calculator" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">smoking time calculator</a>.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 4: Classic Cuts -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">4. Classic Cuts Guides</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl cursor-pointer">
          <summary class="p-5 font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center outline-none">
            Beef Brisket
            <span class="text-[var(--accent-color)] group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">&darr;</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="p-5 pt-0 text-[var(--text-secondary)] border-t border-[var(--border-color)] mt-2">
            <p class="mb-2">The holy grail of BBQ. Brisket consists of two muscles: the lean "flat" and the fatty "point." It requires significant trimming (leaving a 1/4-inch fat cap) and benefits from a simple 50/50 salt and black pepper rub.</p>
            <p>Smoke at 225&deg;F-250&deg;F. Expect a 12-16 hour cook. Wrap tightly in butcher paper when the bark is set and the temp hits the stall (~165&deg;F). Pull when probe tender (around 203&deg;F) and rest in a cooler for at least 2 hours before slicing against the grain.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl cursor-pointer">
          <summary class="p-5 font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center outline-none">
            Pork Shoulder (Pulled Pork)
            <span class="text-[var(--accent-color)] group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">&darr;</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="p-5 pt-0 text-[var(--text-secondary)] border-t border-[var(--border-color)] mt-2">
            <p class="mb-2">The most forgiving cut, perfect for beginners. Use a sweet and savory rub containing brown sugar, paprika, and garlic. Smoke at 250&deg;F with apple or hickory wood.</p>
            <p>Wrap in foil at 165&deg;F, and pull it off the smoker at 200&deg;F-205&deg;F when the bone wiggles freely. Rest for an hour before shredding with meat claws or forks.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl cursor-pointer">
          <summary class="p-5 font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center outline-none">
            Pork Ribs
            <span class="text-[var(--accent-color)] group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">&darr;</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="p-5 pt-0 text-[var(--text-secondary)] border-t border-[var(--border-color)] mt-2">
            <p class="mb-2">Whether you prefer spare ribs or baby backs, always remove the membrane from the back before applying your rub. The 3-2-1 method is popular for spare ribs: 3 hours smoking unwrapped, 2 hours wrapped in foil (with butter, brown sugar, and honey), and 1 hour unwrapped to set a BBQ sauce glaze.</p>
            <p>They are done when the meat pulls back from the bones and the rack bends nearly in half without breaking.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl cursor-pointer">
          <summary class="p-5 font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center outline-none">
            Whole Chicken
            <span class="text-[var(--accent-color)] group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">&darr;</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="p-5 pt-0 text-[var(--text-secondary)] border-t border-[var(--border-color)] mt-2">
            <p class="mb-2">To avoid rubbery skin, poultry requires higher heat. Smoke chicken at 275&deg;F-325&deg;F. Spatchcocking (removing the backbone and flattening the bird) ensures even cooking and crispier skin.</p>
            <p>Use milder woods like apple or cherry. The chicken is safe and juicy when the thickest part of the breast reaches 165&deg;F and the thigh reaches 175&deg;F.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
      <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] italic">Looking for a quick cheat sheet? See our <a href="/guide-smoking-meat" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">Smoking Meat Quick Reference Guide</a>.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 5: Smoker Types Compared -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">5. Smoker Types Compared</h2>
      <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
        <div class="overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse min-w-[600px]">
            <thead>
              <tr class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] border-b border-[var(--border-color)]">
                <th class="p-4 text-[var(--text-secondary)] font-semibold text-sm">Type</th>
                <th class="p-4 text-[var(--text-secondary)] font-semibold text-sm">Pros</th>
                <th class="p-4 text-[var(--text-secondary)] font-semibold text-sm">Cons</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-[var(--border-color)]">
              <tr class="hover:bg-[var(--bg-color)]/50 transition-colors">
                <td class="p-4 font-bold text-white align-top">Offset Smoker<br><span class="text-xs font-normal text-[var(--text-secondary)]">The Traditional Pit</span></td>
                <td class="p-4 text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] align-top"><ul class="list-disc pl-4 space-y-1"><li>Unmatched authentic smoke flavor</li><li>Excellent bark formation</li><li>Large capacity</li></ul></td>
                <td class="p-4 text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] align-top"><ul class="list-disc pl-4 space-y-1"><li>Steep learning curve</li><li>Requires constant fire management</li><li>Heavy and expensive</li></ul></td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="hover:bg-[var(--bg-color)]/50 transition-colors">
                <td class="p-4 font-bold text-white align-top">Pellet Smoker<br><span class="text-xs font-normal text-[var(--text-secondary)]">The Modern Oven</span></td>
                <td class="p-4 text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] align-top"><ul class="list-disc pl-4 space-y-1"><li>Set-and-forget convenience</li><li>Precise digital temp control</li><li>Very beginner-friendly</li></ul></td>
                <td class="p-4 text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] align-top"><ul class="list-disc pl-4 space-y-1"><li>Lighter smoke profile</li><li>Requires electricity</li><li>Moving parts can fail</li></ul></td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="hover:bg-[var(--bg-color)]/50 transition-colors">
                <td class="p-4 font-bold text-white align-top">Kamado<br><span class="text-xs font-normal text-[var(--text-secondary)]">The Ceramic Egg</span></td>
                <td class="p-4 text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] align-top"><ul class="list-disc pl-4 space-y-1"><li>Incredible heat retention</li><li>Highly efficient fuel use</li><li>Versatile (can also sear)</li></ul></td>
                <td class="p-4 text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] align-top"><ul class="list-disc pl-4 space-y-1"><li>Heavy and fragile ceramic</li><li>Hard to lower temps if overshot</li><li>Limited cooking space</li></ul></td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="hover:bg-[var(--bg-color)]/50 transition-colors">
                <td class="p-4 font-bold text-white align-top">Electric Smoker<br><span class="text-xs font-normal text-[var(--text-secondary)]">The Plug & Play</span></td>
                <td class="p-4 text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] align-top"><ul class="list-disc pl-4 space-y-1"><li>Easiest to operate</li><li>Compact footprint</li><li>Good for apartments</li></ul></td>
                <td class="p-4 text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] align-top"><ul class="list-disc pl-4 space-y-1"><li>No smoke ring formation</li><li>Weakest smoke flavor</li><li>Relies on wood chips, not logs</li></ul></td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 6: Rubs & Sauces -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">6. Rubs & Sauces</h2>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-3">The Rub Philosophies</h3>
          <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4"><strong class="text-white">Texas Purist:</strong> For beef, particularly brisket, the standard is equal parts coarse kosher salt and coarse black pepper. Often called Dalmatian rub, this simple mix highlights the beefy flavor without masking the smoke.</p>
          <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><strong class="text-white">Complex Sweet Rubs:</strong> Pork and poultry benefit from complex layers. A classic sweet rub includes brown sugar, paprika (for color), salt, black pepper, garlic powder, onion powder, and a touch of cayenne or chili powder for heat.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-3">Regional Sauce Styles</h3>
          <ul class="space-y-3 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
            <li><strong class="text-[var(--accent-color)]">Kansas City:</strong> The quintessential thick, sweet, and sticky tomato-and-molasses-based sauce.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-[var(--accent-color)]">Carolina Vinegar:</strong> Thin and highly acidic, cutting perfectly through the rich fat of whole hog or pulled pork.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-[var(--accent-color)]">Carolina Mustard:</strong> A tangy, yellow mustard-based sauce popular in South Carolina.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-[var(--accent-color)]">Alabama White:</strong> A unique mayonnaise, vinegar, and black pepper sauce, primarily used for dunking smoked chicken.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 7: Sous Vide + Smoke -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">7. Sous Vide + Smoke</h2>
      <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 shadow-sm flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-6 items-center">
        <div class="flex-1">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-3">The Modern Hybrid Approach</h3>
          <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">Combining the precision of sous vide with the flavor of an offset smoker yields incredibly consistent results with minimal active monitoring. This method is gaining popularity for brisket and ribs.</p>
          <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">The process generally involves smoking the meat for 3 to 4 hours to impart flavor and build a bark, then sealing it in a vacuum bag and finishing the cook in a precision water bath for 24-48 hours. Alternatively, you can sous vide first to tenderize, chill, and then finish on the smoker to rebuild the bark.</p>
          <a href="/sous-vide" class="inline-block mt-2 font-semibold text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">Learn more about Sous Vide Cooking &rarr;</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 8: FAQ -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">8. Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl group">
          <summary class="p-5 font-bold text-white cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center outline-none">
            What temperature to smoke brisket?
            <span class="text-[var(--accent-color)] group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">&darr;</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="p-5 pt-0 text-[var(--text-secondary)] border-t border-[var(--border-color)] mt-2">
            The ideal temperature for smoking a brisket is typically between 225&deg;F and 250&deg;F. Your target internal temperature should be around 200&deg;F to 205&deg;F for optimal tenderness. Let it rest!
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl group">
          <summary class="p-5 font-bold text-white cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center outline-none">
            What is the best wood for smoking?
            <span class="text-[var(--accent-color)] group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">&darr;</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="p-5 pt-0 text-[var(--text-secondary)] border-t border-[var(--border-color)] mt-2">
            The best wood depends on the meat. Hickory and oak are great for robust meats like beef and pork, while milder, sweeter woods like apple and cherry are perfect for poultry and fish.
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl group">
          <summary class="p-5 font-bold text-white cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center outline-none">
            How long to smoke ribs?
            <span class="text-[var(--accent-color)] group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">&darr;</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="p-5 pt-0 text-[var(--text-secondary)] border-t border-[var(--border-color)] mt-2">
            Pork spare ribs generally take 5 to 6 hours. Many pitmasters use the 3-2-1 method: 3 hours unwrapped in smoke, 2 hours wrapped in foil with liquid, and 1 hour unwrapped to set the sauce at 225&deg;F.
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl group">
          <summary class="p-5 font-bold text-white cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center outline-none">
            What is the stall when smoking meat?
            <span class="text-[var(--accent-color)] group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">&darr;</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="p-5 pt-0 text-[var(--text-secondary)] border-t border-[var(--border-color)] mt-2">
            The stall occurs when the internal temperature of large cuts of meat, like brisket or pork shoulder, stops rising (usually around 160&deg;F). This happens because the meat sweats, and evaporative cooling balances the heat of the smoker. Wrapping the meat can help push through the stall.
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl group">
          <summary class="p-5 font-bold text-white cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center outline-none">
            Should I soak my wood chips before smoking?
